We can model an object of the same shape in all kinds of ways. The difference is the underlying geometry. 

Why geometry matters? 

Having the correct geo is very important because the geo determines where the faces are and how they are constructed. Why is that important? Each vertice carries a vertice normal info (basically a vector3 data),  and a face also carries a face normal info which is the average of all the vertice normal info of vertices that construct this face. In rendering, the render engine uses this face normal info to interpret how this polygon should look. 

Then, what geo is correct or not? Most of the time, the geo should follow the shape.

Triangle, Quad, N-gon 

A face can have from three vertices up to unlimited vertices. A face with 3 vertices are called triangle. A face with 4 vertices are called quad, and a face with more than 4 vertices are all called N-gon. For modeling, it is okay to work with triangle and quad, but never N-gon. But when the mesh is sent to game engine, it would be triangulated if it is not, then why do we need to work with triangle and quad but not N-gon? Automatic triangulation with a N-gon would result in many possibilists depending on how many vertices there are, and many of those would have very bad normal info for rendering. With a triangle, there is no other way of interpreting the face normal, so it should be rendered as expected as how we model it. A quad with triangulation would end up with two triangles, so there are two possibilities, a much more precise outcome than a N-gon has, but still chance to go wrong. If it goes wrong, we need to turn it into triangles before we run the automatic triangulation. 

Movie render engine prefers quad over triangle. I don’t know why. But a quad might result in a non flat surface and that is not ideal for rendering.

Smooth operation 

Overall, the smooth operation is trying to pull the mesh itself towards the center of the mesh. In detail, the smooth operation in maya would take a vertice and change its position by pulling it to its neighboring vertices. The further the neighboring vertice is the further it pulls itself to that direction. We can preview the difference by pressing 2 in maya. 

Like this. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To prevent the shape from changing too much, we can add supporting loops, and this technique is called fencing. The tighter the supporting loops are, the less volume of the shape will be changed. 

Like this. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Pressing 3 would preview the smoothed versions of the meshes. 

Like this. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Since smooth operation would take some of the volume out of the mesh, one way we can maintain the targeted volume is the scale the mesh bigger before we do the smooth operation. 

Another issues with smooth operation 

One is the texture stretching, and another is surface stretching. When we do UV unwrap, we have a UV coordinate set right on top of each vertice, when we do smooth operation, how much a vertice moves determines how much texture stretching will be produced. Surface stretching happens when volume loss happens to area we wish to maintain. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

 To fix both issues, we need to add supporting loops as many as we need, for we are running smooth operation on high-poly mesh, and poly count doesn't matter much for high-poly. 

Soften/Harden Edges (Weighted normal technique) 

Tube like mesh do not need too many geo because we would soften the edges(averages the face normal info by the face normal info of the neighboring faces) to make it have nice even shading. 

Like this. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The difference is too small to tell from a relatively far distance. Keep it in mind, we can lower the polygon counts much more than we think.
